observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee, General Services Office (GSO) and the Municipal Accounting Office to prioritize the reconciliation process of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office concerned personnel to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the GSO concerned personnel to keep corresponding Property Cards for control purposes;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE; and
Continue exerting efforts in completing the physical count and in having a complete and accurate RPCPPE in relation to the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that Management:
Enjoin the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
Closely monitor the implementation of all programs/projects/activities (PPAs) under the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund (LDRRMF) to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Direct the LDRRMO to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same;
Advise the Municipal Budget Officer to ascertain that all charges in the LDRRMF are related to four thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management and strictly adhere to the provisions of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC Nos. 2013-1 and 2014-1; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disclosure on the Special Trust Fund for LDRRMF be presented per calendar year in the Notes to FS in accordance with Annex D of COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We reiterated the following to Management,
Require the Inventory Committee to continuously exert utmost effort to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all the LGU’s properties in accordance with the new guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31 2020, prepare and submit, within the deadlines set, the RPCPPE together with the RPCRNS of the LGU;
Instruct the GSO to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, LRNLC, including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the GL account balances and with the property records; and
Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and submit liquidation reports of outstanding fund transfers received from various agencies which purposes were already completed, and return any unspent amount and henceforth, strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 4 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
If the disposition of the unspent/unutilized amount is not provided in the MOA, Trust Agreement or Memorandum of Understanding (MOU), the Agency may, at their option, utilize the said amount by sending a letter to the source agency requesting approval to transfer the unexpended balance to the General Fund (Section 3.2 of COA Circular 2012-001);
Fast track the implementation of the fund transfers since the resources are readily available, and in order not to deprive the Municipality of the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) where the funds are intended for; and
Reconcile the Due to NGAs account and take up the necessary correcting/adjusting entries for fair presentation in the FS.

We recommended that Management require the concerned officials to:
Ensure that the materials distribution or cash assistance program of the BDSIP are supported by approved project proposals with programs of work and approved plans and drawings;
Properly account all the releases of cash or materials, as the case may be, to the recipient barangays;
Monitor at the barangay level the implementation of the intended projects using the cash assistance or materials distributed; and
Submit explanation/justification as well as the lacking supporting documents on the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
Instruct all collectors to prepare RCDs and remit all collections to the Municipal Treasurer at the close of each business day in accordance with Section 29, Vol. I of NGAS Manual. In case of collectors assigned to the field, where travel time from their places of assignment to the Treasurer’s office is more than one day, turnover of collections must be made at least once a week or as soon as the collection reach ₱5,000.00 as prescribed under Section 26 of COA Circular No. 92-382;
Be more prudent in the acknowledgment of remittances in terms of accuracy of the amount and correct serial numbers of accountable forms;
Set control measures to avoid or minimize delayed remittances of collections and institute disciplinary action to concerned accountable employees under his supervision, if necessary; and
Evaluate the existing controls, identify weakness or any deviation from the standard internal control measures in handling accountable forms and undertake steps to improve and/or correct them.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to properly account all the land properties of the Municipality using the cost or fair value and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Land account balance in the Financial Statements in accordance with PPSAS 17 and other applicable accounting standards;
Require the Municipal General Services Officer and the Municipal Assessor to exert effort in the retrieval of land titles and other necessary documents as basis to establish ownership and determine proper valuation;
Allocate adequate budget for the titling of the subject land properties in the name of the Municipal Government to establish absolute ownership and reduce the risk of third party claims;
Make a representation with the Land Registration Authority or Register of Deeds to confirm the ownership of all land properties covered by the Tax Declarations on hand and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto;
Require the Inventory Team to conduct an ocular inspection/physical inventory of the land and determine its exact location and actual use;
Revisit the documentation over the area/s to which the municipal structures/improvements were being constructed/introduced and initiate the determination or assignment of costs to land acquired through a non-exchange transaction;
No further disbursements must be incurred by the Municipality for any introduction of improvement/construction to private lands unless it is clothed with Usufruct Agreement/Acts of Deeds duly notarized and registered in the name of the Municipality before the Register of Deeds. Otherwise, its corresponding disbursements may not be allowed in audit.

