We recommended that Management to require the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit the supporting documents on all the recorded obligations in the Accounts Payable account;
Exert effort to prepare and maintain complete subsidiary ledgers for the said account under all funds;
If the balances could not be substantiated after all remedies were resorted, request for the write-off of account balances in accordance with the prescribed procedures; and
Ensure that all obligations are duly supported with complete documents to prove the validity of the claims before recording it in the books as Accounts Payable or any liability account.

We recommended that Management:
Continue its commitment to faithfully remit trust collections, however, the current administration still has to exert effort in reconciling and establishing the unremitted trust collections from prior years’ transactions and once established, accordingly remit the same to the respective government agencies;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BIR, GSIS, Pag-ibig and Philhealth for any under/over remittances of premiums/contributions and loans to be able to reconcile such records;
Make necessary internal controls that would warrant faithful remittance to the GSIS and/or Pag-ibig of the loan repayments/amortizations for the various loans that were availed by the employees and, at the same time, ensure that the monthly net take home pay of these employees will not be lower than what is prescribed as provided in the General Provision of the GAA after deducting the mandatory contributions and other obligations; and
Require that the Agency Authorized Officer act prudently in approving the loans of the employees with the GSIS and/or Pag-ibig, considering that such approval carries with it the Municipality’s commitment to undertake necessary actions to ensure that the monthly amortizations are deducted from the member-borrower’s monthly salary and remitted to the GSIS and/or Pag-ibig.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Budget Office to make a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account prior years’ experience and statistics as aids in setting targets;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to undertake a review of the present budgeting done under the stewardship of the Municipal Budget Office to set a clearer guide for the concerned revenue generating Departments toward attaining the targets set;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and other Departments involved in generating revenues to meet its targets by conducting periodic review of collection performance by the concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained; and to analyze the reasons for the shortfall in collections and find alternative solution to minimize, reduce or avoid incurrence of shortfall in the future; and
Require the Municipal Budget Office to provide targets for revenue accounts without projected revenues by setting targets based on statistics, prior years’ experiences and future expectations.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the completion/updating of the 10-Year Municipal SWM Plan for approval by the NSWMC to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 26 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes;
Provide the necessary training for SWM collectors and other personnel directly dealing with collection of solid waste to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and
Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

We reiterated, with amendments, the following recommendations to the Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to include in the conduct of the physical count the LGU’s inventories and prepare and submit the Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI);
Require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain an updated Property and Stock Cards and Property and Supplies Ledger Cards, respectively, per category on all PPE and Inventories as recorded in the books of accounts, ensure the maintenance of the same for the recent years’ procurements and continuously work on the old ones;
Require both offices to reconcile property records with the accounting records and give priority in coming up with a reconciled RPCPPE and book balances; and,
Adjust the books of accounts for any reconciling items determined during the process.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasury Office:
Institute control procedures in the testing, sealing, calibration, monitoring and collection of fees from the usage of weights and measures by developing a system of monitoring to ensure renewal of licenses or permits on or before the anniversary dates and maintain adequate records for inspection, calibration and sealing activities;
Conduct periodic testing to provide assurance on the fitness of the weighing instruments for the protection of the buying populace.  Inspection activities must likewise be properly planned for scheduling of personnel and the area to be visited;
Strictly enforce the correct fees for sealing of weights and measures as provided in Section 3K.03 of the Local Revenue Code; and
Enforce strict implementation of Section 3K.08 of the Local Revenue Code particularly on owners found to be committing fraudulent acts as define therein. The consuming public must be guaranteed that weights and measures comply with the standards required by laws and regulations.

We recommended that the Management:
Review and evaluate the manpower resources to ensure adequate staffing pattern that suit the present needs of the municipal offices and stop. Refrain or stop hiring job orders or casuals who are unproductive, unnecessary or whose functions may be dispensed with;
Maximize the use of existing work force and resort to job order hiring only when the implementation of projects and other services justly require it;
Clearly define in the contract the nature of works or activities to be done by the job orders, casuals, contractuals, or holders of contracts of service;
Require the submission of individual accomplishment reports and properly filled-up daily time records to support the payments;
Justify the incurrence of ₱53.89 million, the bulk of which goes to Other General Services and Security Services, and explain why the Management had not procured the latter thru a competitive bidding between security agencies despite the previous year’s audit recommendations, in order to forestall the suspension or disallowance of these transactions; and,
Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to deliberate properly on the appropriate mode of procurement to be used before the LGU procure the needed services giving paramount consideration on pursuing the best interest of the Municipality.

Various inconsistencies were noted in the review and evaluation of the paid payrolls and their supporting documents and out of 2,701, only 304 persons appeared during head count, which casted doubt on the existence and identity of the casuals, contractuals, job orders and holders of contracts of service.
PD No. 1445, or the Government Auditing Code, states that in keeping the accounts, the highest standards of honesty, objectivity and consistency shall be observed to safeguard against inaccurate or misleading information.
In the review and evaluation of sample transactions on payments to casuals, contractuals, JOs and holders of contracts of service, we have noted the following significant inconsistencies, to wit:
Some paid payrolls do not contain any proof of identification of the payees named therein;
The proof of identification of the payees in the payroll were Community Tax Certificate (CTC) Numbers. However, upon verification from the duplicate copy of actual CTCs, it was found that the name of the person in the payroll is different from the name of the person in the duplicate copy of CTC;
All the CTCs indicated as proofs of identification of the payees in a payroll were issued by a single Barangay, but in fact most of them reside in barangays different from the issuing barangay;
The same person has different signatures as are appearing in the paid payroll, actual duplicate copy of CTC and the Daily Time Record;
The DTRs of various persons to support a paid payroll were single-handedly written as depicted by the same stroke and pen color;
The same CTC Reference Number appears in various payroll as proof of identification of different persons;
The same CTC Reference Number appears in the same payroll for the same month as proof of identification of two different persons bearing almost the same name;
The same person indicates different CTC reference numbers as proof of identity; and
Double payments of daily wage to same persons for services rendered on the same month were noted, where some were paid at the same rate, but different number of days paid, while some were paid at a different or higher rate.
Further, during the scheduled head count of all the casuals, contractuals, JOs and holders of contracts of service, who are assigned in the municipal offices, field works or barangays, with total number of 2,701, only 304 persons had appeared and some showed identification (ID) cards and/or CTCs to establish their identities.
Moreover, it was learned that upon payment to the individual payees, the payroll is handed over to a certain office to disburse and release the cash instead of the Disbursing Officer personally disbursing the same at the premises of the Municipal Treasurer’s Office.
The significant inconsistencies in the documents supporting the payments to casuals, contractuals, JOs and holders of contracts of service as are discussed above, as well as the inability to present themselves and establish their identities during the headcount, including the practice of handing over the payroll to the office were the casuals/contractuals/JOs are assigned to disburse and pay the daily wages or monthly honoraria, casted doubt on the existence and identity of the casuals, contractuals, job orders and holders of contracts of service hired by the LGU during CY 2018, hence, would adversely affect the validity, propriety, and legality of the expenditures relative to the contracted services.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Planning and Development Officer abide strictly with the guidelines in the formulation of the 20% Development Plan based on equitable allocation of funds pursuant to Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 of the DILG and DBM;
Implement immediately and on timely basis the identified projects under the 20% DF;
The members of the BAC schedule early all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave way for their timely implementation and completion; and
Refrain from utilizing the developmental fund for non-allowable programs/projects.  The utilized amounts for non-allowable projects must be restituted to the fund in order not to deprive the stakeholders of the benefits they may derived from developmental projects in terms of socio-economic development and environmental management.

a. That the Office of the Municipal Accountant give preferential attention on the preparation and submission of the required bank reconciliation statements pursuant to Section 474 of RA No. 7160 and COA Circular No.96-011 dated October 2, 1996 considering that the variance had already accumulated to a significant amount of P13,001,148.84;
b. That the data reflected in the cash books of the Municipal Treasurer shall preferably be considered in the preparation of the bank reconciliation statements to ensure that any reconciling items will be accordingly adjusted;
c. Any error and reconciling item discovered in the reconciliation process shall accordingly be adjusted in the respective records which need correction/revision, to arrive at a correct and reliable cash in bank balance.

